# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: format-preserving-encryption
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] The **Advanced Encryption Standard** (**AES**), also known by its original name **Rijndael** (Dutch pronunciation: [ˈrɛindaːl], *RAIN-dahl*), is a specification for the encryption of electronic data established by the US National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) in 2001.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] AES is a variant of the Rijndael block cipher developed by two Belgian cryptographers, Joan Daemen and Vincent Rijmen, who submitted a proposal to NIST during the AES selection process.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Rijndael is a family of ciphers with different key and block sizes.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] For AES, NIST selected three members of the Rijndael family, each with a block size of 128 bits, but three different key lengths: 128, 192 and 256 bits.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] AES has been adopted by the US government.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] It supersedes the Data Encryption Standard (DES), which was published in 1977.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] The algorithm described by AES is a symmetric-key algorithm, meaning the same key is used for both encrypting and decrypting the data.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] In the United States, AES was announced by the NIST as the US FIPS PUB 197 (FIPS 197) standard on November 26, 2001.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] This announcement followed a five-year standardization process in which fifteen competing designs were presented and evaluated, before the Rijndael cipher was selected as the most suitable.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] AES is included in the ISO/IEC 18033-3 standard.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] AES became effective as a US federal government standard on May 26, 2002, after approval by US secretary of commerce Donald Evans.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] AES is available in many different encryption packages, and is the first (and only) publicly accessible cipher approved by the US National Security Agency (NSA) for top secret information when used in an NSA approved cryptographic module.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] AES is based on a design principle known as a substitution–permutation network, and is efficient in both software and hardware.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Unlike its predecessor DES, AES does not use a Feistel network.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] AES is a variant of Rijndael, with a fixed block size of 128 bits, and a key size of 128, 192, or 256 bits.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] By contrast, Rijndael *per se* is specified with block and key sizes that may be any multiple of 32 bits, with a minimum of 128 and a maximum of 256 bits.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Most AES calculations are done in a particular finite field.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] The key size used for an AES cipher specifies the number of transformation rounds that convert the input, called the plaintext, into the final output, called the ciphertext.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Each round consists of several processing steps, including one that depends on the encryption key itself.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] A set of reverse rounds are applied to transform ciphertext back into the original plaintext using the same encryption key.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] ShiftRows – a transposition step where the last three rows of the state are shifted cyclically a certain number of steps.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] MixColumns – a linear mixing operation which operates on the columns of the state, combining the four bytes in each column.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] In the SubBytes step, each byte *ai,j* in the *state* array is replaced with a SubByte *S*(*ai,j*) using an 8-bit substitution box.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Before round 0, the *state* array is simply the plaintext/input.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] This operation provides the non-linearity in the cipher.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] The S-box used is derived from the multiplicative inverse over GF(28), known to have good non-linearity properties.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] To avoid attacks based on simple algebraic properties, the S-box is constructed by combining the inverse function with an invertible affine transformation.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] The S-box is also chosen to avoid any fixed points (and so is a derangement), i.e., *S*(*ai,j*) ≠ *ai,j*, and also any opposite fixed points, i.e., *S*(*ai,j*) ⊕ *ai,j* ≠ FF16.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] While performing the decryption, the InvSubBytes step (the inverse of SubBytes) is used, which requires first taking the inverse of the affine transformation and then finding the multiplicative inverse.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] The ShiftRows step operates on the rows of the state; it cyclically shifts the bytes in each row by a certain offset.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] For AES, the first row is left unchanged.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Each byte of the second row is shifted one to the left.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Similarly, the third and fourth rows are shifted by offsets of two and three respectively.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] In this way, each column of the output state of the ShiftRows step is composed of bytes from each column of the input state.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] The importance of this step is to avoid the columns being encrypted independently, in which case AES would degenerate into four independent block ciphers.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] In the MixColumns step, the four bytes of each column of the state are combined using an invertible linear transformation.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] The MixColumns function takes four bytes as input and outputs four bytes, where each input byte affects all four output bytes.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Together with ShiftRows, MixColumns provides diffusion in the cipher.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Matrix multiplication is composed of multiplication and addition of the entries.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Entries are bytes treated as coefficients of polynomial of order *x*7.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Multiplication is modulo irreducible polynomial *x*8 + *x*4 + *x*3 + *x* + 1.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] If processed bit by bit, then, after shifting, a conditional XOR with 1B16 should be performed if the shifted value is larger than FF16 (overflow must be corrected by subtraction of generating polynomial).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] These are special cases of the usual multiplication in GF(28).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] The coefficients are displayed in their hexadecimal equivalent of the binary representation of bit polynomials from GF(28)[*x*].
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] The MixColumns step can also be viewed as a multiplication by the shown particular MDS matrix in the finite field GF(28).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] This process is described further in the article Rijndael MixColumns.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] In the AddRoundKey step, the subkey is combined with the state.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] For each round, a subkey is derived from the main key using Rijndael's key schedule; each subkey is the same size as the state.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] The subkey is added by combining of the state with the corresponding byte of the subkey using bitwise XOR.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] On systems with 32-bit or larger words, it is possible to speed up execution of this cipher by combining the SubBytes and ShiftRows steps with the MixColumns step by transforming them into a sequence of table lookups.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] This requires four 256-entry 32-bit tables (together occupying 4096 bytes).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] A round can then be performed with 16 table lookup operations and 12 32-bit exclusive-or operations, followed by four 32-bit exclusive-or operations in the AddRoundKey step.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Alternatively, the table lookup operation can be performed with a single 256-entry 32-bit table (occupying 1024 bytes) followed by circular rotation operations.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Using a byte-oriented approach, it is possible to combine the SubBytes, ShiftRows, and MixColumns steps into a single round operation.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] The National Security Agency (NSA) reviewed all the AES finalists, including Rijndael, and stated that all of them were secure enough for US Government non-classified data.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] AES has 10 rounds for 128-bit keys, 12 rounds for 192-bit keys, and 14 rounds for 256-bit keys.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] More recent guidance from the NSA, however, only allows classified information to be encrypted with 256-bit key lengths.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] 128-bit and 192-bits is no longer sufficient for the encryption of classified information.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] For cryptographers, a cryptographic "break" is anything faster than a brute-force attack – i.e., performing one trial decryption for each possible key in sequence .
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] A break can thus include results that are infeasible with current technology.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Despite being impractical, theoretical breaks can sometimes provide insight into vulnerability patterns.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] The largest successful publicly known brute-force attack against a widely implemented block-cipher encryption algorithm was against a 64-bit RC5 key by distributed.net in 2006.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] The key space increases by a factor of 2 for each additional bit of key length, and if every possible value of the key is equiprobable; this translates into a doubling of the average brute-force key search time with every additional bit of key length.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] This implies that the effort of a brute-force search increases exponentially with key length.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Key length in itself does not imply security against attacks, since there are ciphers with very long keys that have been found to be vulnerable.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] AES has a fairly simple algebraic framework.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] In 2002, a theoretical attack, named the "XSL attack", was announced by Nicolas Courtois and Josef Pieprzyk, purporting to show a weakness in the AES algorithm, partially due to the low complexity of its nonlinear components.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Since then, other papers have shown that the attack, as originally presented, is unworkable; see XSL attack on block ciphers.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] By 2006, the best known attacks were on 7 rounds for 128-bit keys, 8 rounds for 192-bit keys, and 9 rounds for 256-bit keys.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Until May 2009, the only successful published attacks against the full AES were side-channel attacks on some specific implementations.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] In 2009, a new related-key attack was discovered that exploits the simplicity of AES's key schedule and has a complexity of 2119.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] In December 2009 it was improved to 299.5.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] This is a follow-up to an attack discovered earlier in 2009 by Alex Biryukov, Dmitry Khovratovich, and Ivica Nikolić, with a complexity of 296 for one out of every 235 keys.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] However, related-key attacks are not of concern in any properly designed cryptographic protocol, as a properly designed protocol (i.e., implementational software) will take care not to allow related keys, essentially by constraining an attacker's means of selecting keys for relatedness.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Another attack was blogged by Bruce Schneier on July 30, 2009, and released as a preprint on August 3, 2009.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] 256-bit AES uses 14 rounds, so these attacks are not effective against full AES.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] The practicality of these attacks with stronger related keys has been criticized, for instance, by the paper on chosen-key-relations-in-the-middle attacks on AES-128 authored by Vincent Rijmen in 2010.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] In November 2009, the first known-key distinguishing attack against a reduced 8-round version of AES-128 was released as a preprint.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] This known-key distinguishing attack is an improvement of the rebound, or the start-from-the-middle attack, against AES-like permutations, which view two consecutive rounds of permutation as the application of a so-called Super-S-box.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] It works on the 8-round version of AES-128, with a time complexity of 248, and a memory complexity of 232.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] 128-bit AES uses 10 rounds, so this attack is not effective against full AES-128.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] The first key-recovery attacks on full AES were by Andrey Bogdanov, Dmitry Khovratovich, and Christian Rechberger, and were published in 2011.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] The attack is a biclique attack and is faster than brute force by a factor of about four.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] It requires 2126.2 operations to recover an AES-128 key.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] This result has been further improved to 2126.0 for AES-128, 2189.9 for AES-192, and 2254.3 for AES-256 by Biaoshuai Tao and Hongjun Wu in a 2015 paper, which are the current best results in key recovery attack against AES.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] This is a very small gain, as a 126-bit key (instead of 128 bits) would still take billions of years to brute force on current and foreseeable hardware.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Also, the authors calculate the best attack using their technique on AES with a 128-bit key requires storing 288 bits of data.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] That works out to about 38 trillion terabytes of data, which was more than all the data stored on all the computers on the planet in 2016.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] A paper in 2015 later improved the space complexity to 256 bits, which is 9007 terabytes (while still keeping a time complexity of approximately 2126).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] According to the Snowden documents, the NSA is doing research on whether a cryptographic attack based on tau statistic may help to break AES.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] At present, there is no known practical attack that would allow someone without knowledge of the key to read data encrypted by AES when correctly implemented.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Side-channel attacks do not attack the cipher as a black box, and thus are not related to cipher security as defined in the classical context, but are important in practice.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] They attack implementations of the cipher on hardware or software systems that inadvertently leak data.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] There are several such known attacks on various implementations of AES.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Bernstein announced a cache-timing attack that he used to break a custom server that used OpenSSL's AES encryption.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] The attack required over 200 million chosen plaintexts.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] The custom server was designed to give out as much timing information as possible (the server reports back the number of machine cycles taken by the encryption operation).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] In October 2005, Dag Arne Osvik, Adi Shamir and Eran Tromer presented a paper demonstrating several cache-timing attacks against the implementations in AES found in OpenSSL and Linux's `dm-crypt` partition encryption function.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] One attack was able to obtain an entire AES key after only 800 operations triggering encryptions, in a total of 65 milliseconds.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] This attack requires the attacker to be able to run programs on the same system or platform that is performing AES.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] In December 2009 an attack on some hardware implementations was published that used differential fault analysis and allows recovery of a key with a complexity of 232.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] In November 2010, Endre Bangerter, David Gullasch and Stephan Krenn published a paper which described a practical approach to a "near real time" recovery of secret keys from AES-128 without the need for either cipher text or plaintext.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] The approach also works on AES-128 implementations that use compression tables, such as OpenSSL.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Like some earlier attacks, this one requires the ability to run unprivileged code on the system performing the AES encryption, which may be achieved by malware infection far more easily than commandeering the root account.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] The proposed attack requires standard user privilege and key-retrieval algorithms run under a minute.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Many modern CPUs have built-in hardware instructions for AES, which protect against timing-related side-channel attacks.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] AES-256 is considered to be quantum resistant, as it has similar quantum resistance to AES-128's resistance against traditional, non-quantum, attacks at 128 bits of security.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] AES-192 and AES-128 are not considered quantum resistant due to their smaller key sizes.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] AES-192 has a strength of 96 bits against quantum attacks and AES-128 has 64 bits of strength against quantum attacks, making them both insecure.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] The Cryptographic Module Validation Program (CMVP) is operated jointly by the United States Government's National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) Computer Security Division and the Communications Security Establishment (CSE) of the Government of Canada.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] The use of cryptographic modules validated to NIST FIPS 140-2 is required by the United States Government for encryption of all data that has a classification of Sensitive but Unclassified (SBU) or above.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] The Government of Canada also recommends the use of FIPS 140 validated cryptographic modules in unclassified applications of its departments.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Although NIST publication 197 ("FIPS 197") is the unique document that covers the AES algorithm, vendors typically approach the CMVP under FIPS 140 and ask to have several algorithms (such as Triple DES or SHA1) validated at the same time.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Therefore, it is rare to find cryptographic modules that are uniquely FIPS 197 validated and NIST itself does not generally take the time to list FIPS 197 validated modules separately on its public web site.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Instead, FIPS 197 validation is typically just listed as an "FIPS approved: AES" notation (with a specific FIPS 197 certificate number) in the current list of FIPS 140 validated cryptographic modules.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] The Cryptographic Algorithm Validation Program (CAVP) allows for independent validation of the correct implementation of the AES algorithm.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Successful validation results in being listed on the NIST validations page.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] This testing is a pre-requisite for the FIPS 140-2 module validation.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] However, successful CAVP validation in no way implies that the cryptographic module implementing the algorithm is secure.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] A cryptographic module lacking FIPS 140-2 validation or specific approval by the NSA is not deemed secure by the US Government and cannot be used to protect government data.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] FIPS 140-2 validation is challenging to achieve both technically and fiscally.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] There is a standardized battery of tests as well as an element of source code review that must be passed over a period of a few weeks.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] The cost to perform these tests through an approved laboratory can be significant (e.g., well over US$30,000) and does not include the time it takes to write, test, document and prepare a module for validation.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] After validation, modules must be re-submitted and re-evaluated if they are changed in any way.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] This can vary from simple paperwork updates if the security functionality did not change to a more substantial set of re-testing if the security functionality was impacted by the change.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] Test vectors are a set of known ciphers for a given input and key.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] NIST distributes the reference of AES test vectors as AES Known Answer Test (KAT) Vectors.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] High speed and low RAM requirements were some of the criteria of the AES selection process.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] As the chosen algorithm, AES performed well on a wide variety of hardware, from 8-bit smart cards to high-performance computers.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] On a Pentium Pro, AES encryption requires 18 clock cycles per byte (cpb), equivalent to a throughput of about 11 MiB/s for a 200 MHz processor.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] On Intel Core and AMD Ryzen CPUs supporting AES-NI instruction set extensions, throughput can be multiple GiB/s.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/advanced-encryption-standard] On an Intel Westmere CPU, AES encryption using AES-NI takes about 1.3 cpb for AES-128, and 1.8 cpb for AES-256.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] In cryptography, a **block cipher** is a deterministic algorithm that operates on fixed-length groups of bits, called *blocks*.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Block ciphers are the elementary building blocks of many cryptographic protocols.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] They are ubiquitous in the storage and exchange of data, where such data is secured and authenticated via encryption.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] A block cipher uses blocks as an unvarying transformation.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Even a secure block cipher is suitable for the encryption of only a single block of data at a time, using a fixed key.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] A multitude of modes of operation have been designed to allow their repeated use in a secure way to achieve the other security goals of confidentiality and authenticity.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] However, block ciphers may also feature as building blocks in other cryptographic protocols, such as universal hash functions and pseudorandom number generators.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] A block cipher consists of two paired algorithms, one for encryption, *E*, and the other for decryption, *D*.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Both algorithms accept two inputs: an input block of size *n* bits and a key of size *k* bits; and both yield an *n*-bit output block.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The decryption algorithm *D* is defined to be the inverse function of encryption, i.e., *D* = *E*−1.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] which takes as input a key *K*, of bit length *k* (called the *key size*), and a bit string *P*, of length *n* (called the *block size*), and returns a string *C* of *n* bits.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] *P* is called the plaintext, and *C* is termed the ciphertext.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] For each *K*, the function *E**K*(*P*) is required to be an invertible mapping on {0,1}*n*.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] For example, a block cipher encryption algorithm might take a 128-bit block of plaintext as input, and output a corresponding 128-bit block of ciphertext.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The exact transformation is controlled using a second input – the secret key.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Decryption is similar: the decryption algorithm takes, in this example, a 128-bit block of ciphertext together with the secret key, and yields the original 128-bit block of plain text.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] For each key *K*, *EK* is a permutation (a bijective mapping) over the set of input blocks.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Each key selects one permutation from the set of $(2^{n})!$ possible permutations.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The modern design of block ciphers is based on the concept of an iterated product cipher.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] In his seminal 1949 publication, *Communication Theory of Secrecy Systems*, Claude Shannon analyzed product ciphers and suggested them as a means of effectively improving security by combining simple operations such as substitutions and permutations.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Iterated product ciphers carry out encryption in multiple rounds, each of which uses a different subkey derived from the original key.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] One widespread implementation of such ciphers named a Feistel network after Horst Feistel is notably implemented in the DES cipher.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Many other realizations of block ciphers, such as the AES, are classified as substitution–permutation networks.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The root of all cryptographic block formats used within the Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) and American National Standards Institute (ANSI) standards lies with the Atalla Key Block (AKB), which was a key innovation of the Atalla Box, the first hardware security module (HSM).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Atalla, founder of Atalla Corporation (now Utimaco Atalla), and released in 1973.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The AKB was a key block, which is required to securely interchange symmetric keys or PINs with other actors in the banking industry.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] This secure interchange is performed using the AKB format.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The Atalla Box protected over 90% of all ATM networks in operation as of 1998, and Atalla products still secure the majority of the world's ATM transactions as of 2014.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The publication of the DES cipher by the United States National Bureau of Standards (subsequently the U.S.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] National Institute of Standards and Technology, NIST) in 1977 was fundamental in the public understanding of modern block cipher design.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] It also influenced the academic development of cryptanalytic attacks.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Both differential and linear cryptanalysis arose out of studies on DES design.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] As of 2016, there is a palette of attack techniques against which a block cipher must be secure, in addition to being robust against brute-force attacks.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] where $M_{0}$ is the plaintext and $M_{r}$ the ciphertext, with *r* being the number of rounds.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Frequently, key whitening is used in addition to this.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Given one of the standard iterated block cipher design schemes, it is fairly easy to construct a block cipher that is cryptographically secure, simply by using a large number of rounds.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] However, this will make the cipher inefficient.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Thus, efficiency is the most important additional design criterion for professional ciphers.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Further, a good block cipher is designed to avoid side-channel attacks, such as branch prediction and input-dependent memory accesses that might leak secret data via the cache state or the execution time.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] In addition, the cipher should be concise, for small hardware and software implementations.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] One important type of iterated block cipher known as a *substitution–permutation network (SPN)* takes a block of the plaintext and the key as inputs and applies several alternating rounds consisting of a substitution stage followed by a permutation stage—to produce each block of ciphertext output.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The non-linear substitution stage mixes the key bits with those of the plaintext, creating Shannon's *confusion*.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The linear permutation stage then dissipates redundancies, creating *diffusion*.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] A *substitution box (S-box)* substitutes a small block of input bits with another block of output bits.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] This substitution must be one-to-one, to ensure invertibility (hence decryption).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] A secure S-box will have the property that changing one input bit will change about half of the output bits on average, exhibiting what is known as the avalanche effect—i.e. it has the property that each output bit will depend on every input bit.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] A *permutation box (P-box)* is a permutation of all the bits: it takes the outputs of all the S-boxes of one round, permutes the bits, and feeds them into the S-boxes of the next round.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] A good P-box has the property that the output bits of any S-box are distributed to as many S-box inputs as possible.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] At each round, the round key (obtained from the key with some simple operations, for instance, using S-boxes and P-boxes) is combined using some group operation, typically XOR.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Decryption is done by simply reversing the process (using the inverses of the S-boxes and P-boxes and applying the round keys in reversed order).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] In a *Feistel cipher*, the block of plain text to be encrypted is split into two equal-sized halves.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The round function is applied to one half, using a subkey, and then the output is XORed with the other half.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Let ${\rm {F}}$ be the round function and let $K_{0},K_{1},\ldots ,K_{n}$ be the sub-keys for the rounds $0,1,\ldots ,n$ respectively.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] One advantage of the Feistel model compared to a substitution–permutation network is that the round function ${\rm {F}}$ does not have to be invertible.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The Lai–Massey scheme offers security properties similar to those of the Feistel structure.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] It also shares the advantage that the round function $\mathrm {F}$ does not have to be invertible.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Another similarity is that it also splits the input block into two equal pieces.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] However, the round function is applied to the difference between the two, and the result is then added to both half blocks.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Let $\mathrm {F}$ be the round function and $\mathrm {H}$ a half-round function and let $K_{0},K_{1},\ldots ,K_{n}$ be the sub-keys for the rounds $0,1,\ldots ,n$ respectively.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Many modern block ciphers and hashes are **ARX** algorithms—their round function involves only three operations: (A) modular addition, (R) rotation with fixed rotation amounts, and (X) XOR.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Examples include ChaCha20, Speck, XXTEA, and BLAKE.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Many authors draw an ARX network, a kind of data flow diagram, to illustrate such a round function.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] These ARX operations are popular because they are relatively fast and cheap in hardware and software, their implementation can be made extremely simple, and also because they run in constant time, and therefore are immune to timing attacks.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The rotational cryptanalysis technique attempts to attack such round functions.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Other operations often used in block ciphers include data-dependent rotations as in RC5 and RC6, a substitution box implemented as a lookup table as in Data Encryption Standard and Advanced Encryption Standard, a permutation box, and multiplication as in IDEA.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] A block cipher by itself allows encryption only of a single data block of the cipher's block length.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] For a variable-length message, the data must first be partitioned into separate cipher blocks.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] In the simplest case, known as electronic codebook (ECB) mode, a message is first split into separate blocks of the cipher's block size (possibly extending the last block with padding bits), and then each block is encrypted and decrypted independently.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] However, such a naive method is generally insecure because equal plaintext blocks will always generate equal ciphertext blocks (for the same key), so patterns in the plaintext message become evident in the ciphertext output.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] To overcome this limitation, several so-called block cipher modes of operation have been designed and specified in national recommendations such as NIST 800-38A and BSI TR-02102 and international standards such as ISO/IEC 10116.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The general concept is to use randomization of the plaintext data based on an additional input value, frequently called an initialization vector, to create what is termed probabilistic encryption.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] In the popular cipher block chaining (CBC) mode, for encryption to be secure the initialization vector passed along with the plaintext message must be a random or pseudo-random value, which is added in an exclusive-or manner to the first plaintext block before it is encrypted.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The resultant ciphertext block is then used as the new initialization vector for the next plaintext block.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] In the cipher feedback (CFB) mode, which emulates a self-synchronizing stream cipher, the initialization vector is first encrypted and then added to the plaintext block.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The output feedback (OFB) mode repeatedly encrypts the initialization vector to create a key stream for the emulation of a synchronous stream cipher.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] From a security-theoretic point of view, modes of operation must provide what is known as semantic security.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Informally, it means that given some ciphertext under an unknown key one cannot practically derive any information from the ciphertext (other than the length of the message) over what one would have known without seeing the ciphertext.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] It has been shown that all of the modes discussed above, with the exception of the ECB mode, provide this property under so-called chosen plaintext attacks.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Some modes such as the CBC mode only operate on complete plaintext blocks.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Simply extending the last block of a message with zero bits is insufficient since it does not allow a receiver to easily distinguish messages that differ only in the number of padding bits.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] More importantly, such a simple solution gives rise to very efficient padding oracle attacks.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] A suitable padding scheme is therefore needed to extend the last plaintext block to the cipher's block size.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Cryptanalysis is the technique in which ciphers are decrypted without knowledge of the used key.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] This property results in the cipher's security degrading quadratically, and needs to be taken into account when selecting a block size.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] There is a trade-off though as large block sizes can result in the algorithm becoming inefficient to operate.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Earlier block ciphers such as the DES have typically selected a 64-bit block size, while newer designs such as the AES support block sizes of 128 bits or more, with some ciphers supporting a range of different block sizes.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The discovery is attributed to Mitsuru Matsui, who first applied the technique to the FEAL cipher (Matsui and Yamagishi, 1992).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] For a new block cipher design to have any credibility, it must demonstrate evidence of security against known attacks.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] When a block cipher is used in a given mode of operation, the resulting algorithm should ideally be about as secure as the block cipher itself.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] ECB (discussed above) emphatically lacks this property: regardless of how secure the underlying block cipher is, ECB mode can easily be attacked.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] On the other hand, CBC mode can be proven to be secure under the assumption that the underlying block cipher is likewise secure.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Note, however, that making statements like this requires formal mathematical definitions for what it means for an encryption algorithm or a block cipher to "be secure".
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] This section describes two common notions for what properties a block cipher should have.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Each corresponds to a mathematical model that can be used to prove properties of higher-level algorithms, such as CBC.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] This general approach to cryptography – proving higher-level algorithms (such as CBC) are secure under explicitly stated assumptions regarding their components (such as a block cipher) – is known as *provable security*.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Informally, a block cipher is secure in the standard model if an attacker cannot tell the difference between the block cipher (equipped with a random key) and a random permutation.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] To be a bit more precise, let *E* be an *n*-bit block cipher.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The attacker chooses an *n*-bit string *X*, and the person running the game tells him the value of *f*(*X*).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Step 2 is repeated a total of *q* times.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The attacker guesses how the coin landed.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The attacker, which we can model as an algorithm, is called an *adversary*.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The function *f* (which the adversary was able to query) is called an *oracle*.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Note that an adversary can trivially ensure a 50% chance of winning simply by guessing at random (or even by, for example, always guessing "heads").
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Therefore, let *P**E*(*A*) denote the probability that adversary *A* wins this game against *E*, and define the *advantage* of *A* as 2(*P**E*(*A*) − 1/2).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] It follows that if *A* guesses randomly, its advantage will be 0; on the other hand, if *A* always wins, then its advantage is 1.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The block cipher *E* is a *pseudo-random permutation* (PRP) if no adversary has an advantage significantly greater than 0, given specified restrictions on *q* and the adversary's running time.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] If in Step 2 above adversaries have the option of learning *f*−1(*X*) instead of *f*(*X*) (but still have only small advantages) then *E* is a *strong* PRP (SPRP).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] An adversary is *non-adaptive* if it chooses all *q* values for *X* before the game begins (that is, it does not use any information gleaned from previous queries to choose each *X* as it goes).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] These definitions have proven useful for analyzing various modes of operation.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] For example, one can define a similar game for measuring the security of a block cipher-based encryption algorithm, and then try to show (through a reduction argument) that the probability of an adversary winning this new game is not much more than *P**E*(*A*) for some *A*.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] (The reduction typically provides limits on *q* and the running time of *A*.) Equivalently, if *P**E*(*A*) is small for all relevant *A*, then no attacker has a significant probability of winning the new game.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] This formalizes the idea that the higher-level algorithm inherits the block cipher's security.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Block ciphers may be evaluated according to multiple criteria in practice.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Lucifer is generally considered to be the first civilian block cipher, developed at IBM in the 1970s based on work done by Horst Feistel.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] A revised version of the algorithm was adopted as a U.S. government Federal Information Processing Standard: FIPS PUB 46 Data Encryption Standard (DES).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] National Bureau of Standards (NBS) after a public invitation for submissions and some internal changes by NBS (and, potentially, the NSA).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] DES was publicly released in 1976 and has been widely used.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] DES was designed to, among other things, resist a certain cryptanalytic attack known to the NSA and rediscovered by IBM, though unknown publicly until rediscovered again and published by Eli Biham and Adi Shamir in the late 1980s.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The technique is called differential cryptanalysis and remains one of the few general attacks against block ciphers; linear cryptanalysis is another but may have been unknown even to the NSA, prior to its publication by Mitsuru Matsui.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] DES prompted a large amount of other work and publications in cryptography and cryptanalysis in the open community and it inspired many new cipher designs.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] DES has a block size of 64 bits and a key size of 56 bits.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] 64-bit blocks became common in block cipher designs after DES.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Key length depended on several factors, including government regulation.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Many observers in the 1970s commented that the 56-bit key length used for DES was too short.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] As time went on, its inadequacy became apparent, especially after a special-purpose machine designed to break DES was demonstrated in 1998 by the Electronic Frontier Foundation.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] An extension to DES, Triple DES, triple-encrypts each block with either two independent keys (112-bit key and 80-bit security) or three independent keys (168-bit key and 112-bit security).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] As of 2011, the three-key version is still considered secure, though the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) standards no longer permit the use of the two-key version in new applications, due to its 80-bit security level.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The *International Data Encryption Algorithm* (*IDEA*) is a block cipher designed by James Massey of ETH Zurich and Xuejia Lai; it was first described in 1991, as an intended replacement for DES.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] IDEA operates on 64-bit blocks using a 128-bit key and consists of a series of eight identical transformations (a *round*) and an output transformation (the *half-round*).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The processes for encryption and decryption are similar.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] IDEA derives much of its security by interleaving operations from different groups – modular addition and multiplication, and bitwise *exclusive or (XOR)* – which are algebraically "incompatible" in some sense.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The designers analysed IDEA to measure its strength against differential cryptanalysis and concluded that it is immune under certain assumptions.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] No successful linear or algebraic weaknesses have been reported.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] As of 2012, the best attack which applies to all keys can break a full 8.5-round IDEA using a narrow-bicliques attack about four times faster than brute force.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] RC5 is a block cipher designed by Ronald Rivest in 1994 which, unlike many other ciphers, has a variable block size (32, 64, or 128 bits), key size (0 to 2040 bits), and a number of rounds (0 to 255).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The original suggested choice of parameters was a block size of 64 bits, a 128-bit key, and 12 rounds.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] A key feature of RC5 is the use of data-dependent rotations; one of the goals of RC5 was to prompt the study and evaluation of such operations as a cryptographic primitive.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] RC5 also consists of a number of modular additions and XORs.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The general structure of the algorithm is a Feistel-like a network.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The encryption and decryption routines can be specified in a few lines of code.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The key schedule, however, is more complex, expanding the key using an essentially one-way function with the binary expansions of both e and the golden ratio as sources of "nothing up my sleeve numbers".
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The tantalizing simplicity of the algorithm together with the novelty of the data-dependent rotations has made RC5 an attractive object of study for cryptanalysts.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] 12-round RC5 (with 64-bit blocks) is susceptible to a differential attack using 244 chosen plaintexts.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] 18–20 rounds are suggested as sufficient protection.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The *Rijndael* cipher developed by Belgian cryptographers, Joan Daemen and Vincent Rijmen was one of the competing designs to replace DES.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] It won the 5-year public competition to become the AES (Advanced Encryption Standard).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Adopted by NIST in 2001, AES has a fixed block size of 128 bits and a key size of 128, 192, or 256 bits, whereas Rijndael can be specified with block and key sizes in any multiple of 32 bits, with a minimum of 128 bits.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The block size has a maximum of 256 bits, but the key size has no theoretical maximum.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] AES operates on a 4×4 column-major order matrix of bytes, termed the *state* (versions of Rijndael with a larger block size have additional columns in the state).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] It was designed as a general-purpose algorithm, intended as an alternative to the aging DES and free of the problems and constraints associated with other algorithms.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] At the time Blowfish was released, many other designs were proprietary, encumbered by patents, or were commercial/government secrets.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Schneier has stated that "Blowfish is unpatented, and will remain so in all countries.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The algorithm is hereby placed in the public domain, and can be freely used by anyone." The same applies to Twofish, a successor algorithm from Schneier.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Wagner have described a generalized version of block ciphers called "tweakable" block ciphers.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] A tweakable block cipher accepts a second input called the *tweak* along with its usual plaintext or ciphertext input.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The tweak, along with the key, selects the permutation computed by the cipher.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] If changing tweaks is sufficiently lightweight (compared with a usually fairly expensive key setup operation), then some interesting new operation modes become possible.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] The disk encryption theory article describes some of these modes.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Block ciphers traditionally work over a binary alphabet.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] That is, both the input and the output are binary strings, consisting of *n* zeroes and ones.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] In some situations, however, one may wish to have a block cipher that works over some other alphabet; for example, encrypting 16-digit credit card numbers in such a way that the ciphertext is also a 16-digit number might facilitate adding an encryption layer to legacy software.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] This is an example of *format-preserving encryption*.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] More generally, format-preserving encryption requires a keyed permutation on some finite language.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] This makes format-preserving encryption schemes a natural generalization of (tweakable) block ciphers.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] In contrast, traditional encryption schemes, such as CBC, are not permutations because the same plaintext can encrypt multiple different ciphertexts, even when using a fixed key.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Block ciphers can be used to build other cryptographic primitives, such as those below.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] For these other primitives to be cryptographically secure, care has to be taken to build them the right way.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Just as block ciphers can be used to build hash functions, like SHA-1 and SHA-2 are based on block ciphers which are also used independently as SHACAL, hash functions can be used to build block ciphers.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/block-cipher] Examples of such block ciphers are BEAR and LION.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/ciphertext] In cryptography, **ciphertext** or **cyphertext** is the result of encryption performed on plaintext using an algorithm, called a cipher.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/ciphertext] Ciphertext is also known as encrypted or encoded information because it contains a form of the original plaintext that is unreadable by a human or computer without the proper cipher to decrypt it.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/ciphertext] This process prevents the loss of sensitive information via hacking.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/ciphertext] Decryption, the inverse of encryption, is the process of turning ciphertext into readable plaintext.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/ciphertext] Ciphertext is not to be confused with codetext, because the latter is a result of a code, not a cipher.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/ciphertext] Let $m\!$ be the plaintext message that Alice wants to secretly transmit to Bob and let $E_{k}\!$ be the encryption cipher, where $_{k}\!$ is a cryptographic key.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/ciphertext] In a symmetric-key system, Bob knows Alice's encryption key.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/ciphertext] Once the message is encrypted, Alice can safely transmit it to Bob (assuming no one else knows the key).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/ciphertext] Alternatively, in a non-symmetric key system, everyone, not just Alice and Bob, knows the encryption key; but the decryption key cannot be inferred from the encryption key.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/ciphertext] The history of cryptography began thousands of years ago.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/ciphertext] Cryptography uses a variety of different types of encryption.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/ciphertext] Earlier algorithms were performed by hand and are substantially different from modern algorithms, which are generally executed by a machine.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/ciphertext] Historical pen and paper ciphers used in the past are sometimes known as classical ciphers.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/ciphertext] Historical ciphers are not generally used as a standalone encryption technique because they are quite easy to crack.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/ciphertext] Many of the classical ciphers, with the exception of the one-time pad, can be cracked using brute force.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/ciphertext] Modern ciphers are more secure than classical ciphers and are designed to withstand a wide range of attacks.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/ciphertext] An attacker should not be able to find the key used in a modern cipher, even if they know any specifics about the plaintext and its corresponding ciphertext.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/ciphertext] In a symmetric key algorithm (e.g., DES, AES), the sender and receiver have a shared key established in advance: the sender uses the shared key to perform encryption; the receiver uses the shared key to perform decryption.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/ciphertext] Symmetric key algorithms can either be block ciphers or stream ciphers.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/ciphertext] Block ciphers operate on fixed-length groups of bits, called blocks, with an unvarying transformation.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/ciphertext] Stream ciphers encrypt plaintext digits one at a time on a continuous stream of data, with the transformation of successive digits varying during the encryption process.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/ciphertext] In an asymmetric key algorithm (e.g., RSA), there are two different keys: a *public key* and a *private key.* The *public key* is published, thereby allowing any sender to perform encryption.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/ciphertext] The *private key* is kept secret by the receiver, thereby allowing only the receiver to correctly perform decryption.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/ciphertext] Cryptanalysis (also referred to as codebreaking or cracking the code) is the study of applying various methodologies to obtain the meaning of encrypted information, without having access to the cipher required to correctly decrypt the information.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/ciphertext] This typically involves gaining an understanding of the system design and determining the cipher.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/ciphertext] Cryptanalysts can follow one or more attack models to crack a cipher, depending upon what information is available and the type of cipher being analyzed.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/ciphertext] Ciphertext is generally the most easily obtained part of a cryptosystem and therefore is an important part of cryptanalysis.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] A large number of block ciphers use the scheme, including the US Data Encryption Standard, the Soviet/Russian GOST (aka Magma) and the more recent Blowfish and Twofish ciphers.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] In a Feistel cipher, encryption and decryption are very similar operations, and both consist of iteratively running a function called a "round function" a fixed number of times.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] Many modern symmetric block ciphers are based on Feistel networks.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] Feistel networks were first seen commercially in IBM's Lucifer cipher, designed by Horst Feistel and Don Coppersmith in 1973.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] Feistel networks gained respectability when the U.S.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] Federal Government adopted the DES (a cipher based on Lucifer, with changes made by the NSA) in 1976.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] Like other components of the DES, the iterative nature of the Feistel construction makes implementing the cryptosystem in hardware easier (particularly on the hardware available at the time of DES's design).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] A Feistel network uses a *round function*, a function which takes two inputs – a data block and a subkey – and returns one output of the same size as the data block.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] In each round, the round function is run on half of the data to be encrypted, and its output is XORed with the other half of the data.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] This is repeated a fixed number of times, and the final output is the encrypted data.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] An important advantage of Feistel networks compared to other cipher designs such as substitution–permutation networks (SP-networks) is that the entire operation is guaranteed to be invertible (that is, encrypted data can be decrypted), even if the round function is not itself invertible.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] The round function can be made arbitrarily complicated, since it does not need to be designed to be invertible.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] Furthermore, the encryption and decryption operations are very similar, even identical in some cases, requiring only a reversal of the key schedule.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] Therefore, the size of the code or circuitry required to implement such a cipher is nearly halved.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] Unlike SP-networks, Feistel networks also do not depend on a substitution box that could cause timing side-channels in software implementations.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] The structure and properties of Feistel ciphers have been extensively analyzed by cryptographers.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] Because of this very important result of Luby and Rackoff, Feistel ciphers are sometimes called Luby–Rackoff block ciphers.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] Further theoretical work has generalized the construction somewhat and given more precise bounds for security.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] Let $\mathrm {F}$ be the round function and let $K_{0},K_{1},\ldots ,K_{n}$ be the sub-keys for the rounds $0,1,\ldots ,n$ respectively.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] Split the plaintext block into two equal pieces: ( $L_{0}$ , $R_{0}$ ).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] The diagram illustrates both encryption and decryption.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] Note the reversal of the subkey order for decryption; this is the only difference between encryption and decryption.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] Unbalanced Feistel ciphers use a modified structure where $L_{0}$ and $R_{0}$ are not of equal lengths.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] The Skipjack cipher is an example of such a cipher.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] The Texas Instruments digital signature transponder uses a proprietary unbalanced Feistel cipher to perform challenge–response authentication.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] The Thorp shuffle is an extreme case of an unbalanced Feistel cipher in which one side is a single bit.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] This has better provable security than a balanced Feistel cipher but requires more rounds.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] There exists Type-1, Type-2, and Type-3 Feistel networks, where the Feistel function is one fourth the size of the block but operates a varying number of times within one round.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] The Feistel construction is also used in cryptographic algorithms other than block ciphers.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] For example, the optimal asymmetric encryption padding (OAEP) scheme uses a simple Feistel network to randomize ciphertexts in certain asymmetric-key encryption schemes.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] A generalized Feistel algorithm can be used to create strong permutations on small domains of size not a power of two (see format-preserving encryption).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] Whether the entire cipher is a Feistel cipher or not, Feistel-like networks can be used as a component of a cipher's design.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/feistel-cipher] For example, MISTY1 is a Feistel cipher using a three-round Feistel network in its round function, Skipjack is a modified Feistel cipher using a Feistel network in its G permutation, and Threefish (part of Skein) is a non-Feistel block cipher that uses a Feistel-like MIX function.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] In cryptography, **format-preserving encryption** (**FPE**), refers to encrypting in such a way that the output (the ciphertext) is in the same format as the input (the plaintext).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] Typically only finite sets of characters are used; numeric, alphabetic or alphanumeric.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] For such finite domains, and for the purposes of the discussion below, the cipher is equivalent to a permutation of *N* integers {0, ... , *N*−1} where *N* is the size of the domain.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] One motivation for using FPE comes from the problems associated with integrating encryption into existing applications, with well-defined data models.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] A typical example would be a credit card number, such as `1234567812345670` (16 bytes long, digits only).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] Adding encryption to such applications might be challenging if data models are to be changed, as it usually involves changing field length limits or data types.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] For example, output from a typical block cipher would turn credit card number into a hexadecimal (e.g.`0x96a45cbcf9c2a9425cde9e274948cb67`, 34 bytes, hexadecimal digits) or Base64 value (e.g.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] `lqRcvPnCqUJc3p4nSUjLZw==`, 24 bytes, alphanumeric and special characters), which will break any existing applications expecting the credit card number to be a 16-digit number.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] Apart from simple formatting problems, using AES-128-CBC, this credit card number might get encrypted to the hexadecimal value `0xde015724b081ea7003de4593d792fd8b695b39e095c98f3a220ff43522a2df02`.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] In addition to the problems caused by creating invalid characters and increasing the size of the data, data encrypted using the CBC mode of an encryption algorithm also changes its value when it is decrypted and encrypted again.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] This happens because the random seed value that is used to initialize the encryption algorithm and is included as part of the encrypted value is different for each encryption operation.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] Because of this, it is impossible to use data that has been encrypted with the CBC mode as a unique key to identify a row in a database.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] FPE attempts to simplify the transition process by preserving the formatting and length of the original data, allowing a drop-in replacement of plaintext values with their ciphertexts in legacy applications.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] Although a truly random permutation is the ideal FPE cipher, for large domains it is infeasible to pre-generate and remember a truly random permutation.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] So the problem of FPE is to generate a pseudorandom permutation from a secret key, in such a way that the computation time for a single value is small (ideally constant, but most importantly smaller than *O(N)*).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] An *n*-bit block cipher technically *is* a FPE on the set {0, ..., 2*n*-1}.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] If an FPE is needed on one of these standard sized sets (for example, *n* = 64 for DES and *n* = 128 for AES) a block cipher of the right size can be used.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] However, in typical usage, a block cipher is used in a mode of operation that allows it to encrypt arbitrarily long messages, and with an initialization vector as discussed above.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] In this mode, a block cipher is not an FPE.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] In cryptographic literature (see most of the references below), the measure of a "good" FPE is whether an attacker can distinguish the FPE from a truly random permutation.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] Various types of attackers are postulated, depending on whether they have access to oracles or known ciphertext/plaintext pairs.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] In most of the approaches listed here, a well-understood block cipher (such as AES) is used as a primitive to take the place of an ideal random function.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] This has the advantage that incorporation of a secret key into the algorithm is easy.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] Where AES is mentioned in the following discussion, any other good block cipher would work as well.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] Implementing FPE with security provably related to that of the underlying block cipher was first undertaken in a paper by cryptographers John Black and Phillip Rogaway, which described three ways to do this.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] They proved that each of these techniques is as secure as the block cipher that is used to construct it.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] This means that if the AES algorithm is used to create an FPE algorithm, then the resulting FPE algorithm is as secure as AES because an adversary capable of defeating the FPE algorithm can also defeat the AES algorithm.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] Therefore, if AES is secure, then the FPE algorithms constructed from it are also secure.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] In all of the following, *E* denotes the AES encryption operation that is used to construct an FPE algorithm and *F* denotes the FPE encryption operation.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] One simple way to create an FPE algorithm on {0, ..., *N*-1} is to assign a pseudorandom weight to each integer, then sort by weight.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] The weights are defined by applying an existing block cipher to each integer.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] Black and Rogaway call this technique a "prefix cipher" and showed it was provably as good as the block cipher used.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] This method is only useful for small values of *N*.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] For larger values, the size of the lookup table and the required number of encryptions to initialize the table gets too big to be practical.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] If there is a set *M* of allowed values within the domain of a pseudorandom permutation *P* (for example *P* can be a block cipher like AES), an FPE algorithm can be created from the block cipher by repeatedly applying the block cipher until the result is one of the allowed values (within *M*).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] The recursion is guaranteed to terminate.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] This has the advantage that the elements of *M* do not have to be mapped to a consecutive sequence {0,...,*N*-1} of integers.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] It has the disadvantage, when *M* is much smaller than *P*'s domain, that too many iterations might be required for each operation.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] If *P* is a block cipher of a fixed size, such as AES, this is a severe restriction on the sizes of *M* for which this method is efficient.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] For example, an application may want to encrypt 100-bit values with AES in a way that creates another 100-bit value.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] With this technique, AES-128-ECB encryption can be applied until it reaches a value which has all of its 28 highest bits set to 0, which will take an average of 228 iterations to happen.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] It is also possible to make a FPE algorithm using a Feistel network.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] A Feistel network needs a source of pseudo-random values for the sub-keys for each round, and the output of the AES algorithm can be used as these pseudo-random values.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] When this is done, the resulting Feistel construction is good if enough rounds are used.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] One way to implement an FPE algorithm using AES and a Feistel network is to use as many bits of AES output as are needed to equal the length of the left or right halves of the Feistel network.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] If a 24-bit value is needed as a sub-key, for example, it is possible to use the lowest 24 bits of the output of AES for this value.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] This may not result in the output of the Feistel network preserving the format of the input, but it is possible to iterate the Feistel network in the same way that the cycle-walking technique does to ensure that format can be preserved.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] Because it is possible to adjust the size of the inputs to a Feistel network, it is possible to make it very likely that this iteration ends very quickly on average.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] A Thorp shuffle is like an idealized card-shuffle, or equivalently a maximally-unbalanced Feistel cipher where one side is a single bit.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] It is easier to prove security for unbalanced Feistel ciphers than for balanced ones.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] For domain sizes that are a power of two, and an existing block cipher with a smaller block size, a new cipher may be created using VIL mode as described by Bellare, Rogaway.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] The Hasty Pudding Cipher uses custom constructions (not depending on existing block ciphers as primitives) to encrypt arbitrary finite small domains.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] The FFSEM mode of AES (specification) that has been accepted for consideration by NIST uses the Feistel network construction of Black and Rogaway described above, with AES for the round function, with one slight modification: a single key is used and is tweaked slightly for each round.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] As of February 2010, FFSEM has been superseded by the FFX mode written by Mihir Bellare, Phillip Rogaway, and Terence Spies.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] (specification, **NIST Block Cipher Modes Development*, 2010*).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] In JPEG 2000 standard, the marker codes (in the range 0xFF90 through 0xFFFF) should not appear in the plaintext and ciphertext.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] The simple modular-0xFF90 technique cannot be applied to solve the JPEG 2000 encryption problem.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] For example, the ciphertext words 0x23FF and 0x9832 are valid, but their combination 0x23FF9832 becomes invalid since it introduces the marker code 0xFF98.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] Similarly, the simple cycle-walking technique cannot be applied to solve the JPEG2000 encryption problem since two valid ciphertext blocks may give invalid ciphertext when they get combined.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] For example, if the first ciphertext block ends with bytes "...30FF" and the second ciphertext block starts with bytes "9832...", then the marker code "0xFF98" would appear in the ciphertext.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] Two mechanisms for format-preserving encryption of JPEG 2000 were given in the paper "Efficient and Secure Encryption Schemes for JPEG2000" by Hongjun Wu and Di Ma.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] To perform format-preserving encryption of JPEG 2000, the technique is to exclude the byte "0xFF" in the encryption and decryption.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] Then a JPEG 2000 encryption mechanism performs modulo-n addition with stream cipher; another JPEG 2000 encryption mechanism performs the cycle-walking technique with block cipher.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] Several FPE constructs are based on adding the output of a standard cipher, modulo n, to the data to be encrypted, with various methods of unbiasing the result.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] The modulo-n addition shared by many of the constructs is the immediately obvious solution to the FPE problem (thus its use in a number of cases), with the main differences being the unbiasing mechanisms used.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] This standard was withdrawn on May 19, 2005, so the technique should be considered obsolete in terms of being a formal standard.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] The paper "Using Datatype-Preserving Encryption to Enhance Data Warehouse Security" by Michael Brightwell and Harry Smith describes a way to use the DES encryption algorithm in a way that preserves the format of the plaintext.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] This technique doesn't appear to apply an unbiasing step as do the other modulo-n techniques referenced here.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] The paper "Format-Preserving Encryption" by Mihir Bellare and Thomas Ristenpart describes using "nearly balanced" Feistel networks to create secure FPE algorithms.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] The paper "Format Controlling Encryption Using Datatype Preserving Encryption" by Ulf Mattsson describes other ways to create FPE algorithms.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] An example of FPE algorithm is FNR (*Flexible Naor and Reingold*).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] NIST Special Publication 800-38G, "Recommendation for Block Cipher Modes of Operation: Methods for Format-Preserving Encryption" specifies two methods: FF1 and FF3.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] Details on the proposals submitted for each can be found at the NIST Block Cipher Modes Development site, including patent and test vector information.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] Sample values are available for both FF1 and FF3.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] Another mode was included in the draft NIST guidance but was removed before final publication.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/format-preserving-encryption] Korea has also developed a FPE standard, FEA-1 and FEA-2.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] The tokenization system must be secured and validated using security best practices applicable to sensitive data protection, secure storage, audit, authentication and authorization.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] The tokenization system provides data processing applications with the authority and interfaces to request tokens, or detokenize back to sensitive data.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] The security and risk reduction benefits of tokenization require that the tokenization system is logically isolated and segmented from data processing systems and applications that previously processed or stored sensitive data replaced by tokens.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Only the tokenization system can tokenize data to create tokens, or detokenize back to redeem sensitive data under strict security controls.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] The token generation method must be proven to have the property that there is no feasible means through direct attack, cryptanalysis, side channel analysis, token mapping table exposure or brute force techniques to reverse tokens back to live data.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Replacing live data with tokens in systems is intended to minimize exposure of sensitive data to those applications, stores, people and processes, reducing risk of compromise or accidental exposure and unauthorized access to sensitive data.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Applications can operate using tokens instead of live data, with the exception of a small number of trusted applications explicitly permitted to detokenize when strictly necessary for an approved business purpose.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization systems may be operated in-house within a secure isolated segment of the data center, or as a service from a secure service provider.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization may be used to safeguard sensitive data involving, for example, bank accounts, financial statements, medical records, criminal records, driver's licenses, loan applications, stock trades, voter registrations, and other types of personally identifiable information (PII).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization is often used in credit card processing.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] The PCI Council defines tokenization as "a process by which the primary account number (PAN) is replaced with a surrogate value called a token.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] A PAN may be linked to a reference number through the tokenization process.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] In this case, the merchant simply has to retain the token and a reliable third party controls the relationship and holds the PAN.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] The token may be created independently of the PAN, or the PAN can be used as part of the data input to the tokenization technique.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] The communication between the merchant and the third-party supplier must be secure to prevent an attacker from intercepting to gain the PAN and the token.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] De-tokenization is the reverse process of redeeming a token for its associated PAN value.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] The security of an individual token relies predominantly on the infeasibility of determining the original PAN knowing only the surrogate value".
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] The choice of tokenization as an alternative to other techniques such as encryption will depend on varying regulatory requirements, interpretation, and acceptance by respective auditing or assessment entities.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] This is in addition to any technical, architectural or operational constraint that tokenization imposes in practical use.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] The concept of tokenization, as adopted by the industry today, has existed since the first currency systems emerged centuries ago as a means to reduce risk in handling high value financial instruments by replacing them with surrogate equivalents.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] In the physical world, coin tokens have a long history of use replacing the financial instrument of minted coins and banknotes.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] In more recent history, subway tokens and casino chips found adoption for their respective systems to replace physical currency and cash handling risks such as theft.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Exonumia and scrip are terms synonymous with such tokens.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] In the digital world, similar substitution techniques have been used since the 1970s as a means to isolate real data elements from exposure to other data systems.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] In databases for example, surrogate key values have been used since 1976 to isolate data associated with the internal mechanisms of databases and their external equivalents for a variety of uses in data processing.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] More recently, these concepts have been extended to consider this isolation tactic to provide a security mechanism for the purposes of data protection.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] In the payment card industry, tokenization is one means of protecting sensitive cardholder data in order to comply with industry standards and government regulations.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization was applied to payment card data by Shift4 Corporation and released to the public during an industry Security Summit in Las Vegas, Nevada in 2005.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] The technology is meant to prevent the theft of the credit card information in storage.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Shift4 defines tokenization as: "The concept of using a non-decryptable piece of data to represent, by reference, sensitive or secret data.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] To protect data over its full lifecycle, tokenization is often combined with end-to-end encryption to secure data in transit to the tokenization system or service, with a token replacing the original data on return.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] For example, to avoid the risks of malware stealing data from low-trust systems such as point of sale (POS) systems, as in the Target breach of 2013, cardholder data encryption must take place prior to card data entering the POS and not after.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] The PCI Council has also specified end-to-end encryption (certified point-to-point encryption—P2PE) for various service implementations in various PCI Council Point-to-point Encryption documents.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization systems share several components according to established standards.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Token mapping – this is the process of assigning the created token value to its original value.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] To enable permitted look-ups of the original value using the token as the index, a secure cross-reference database must be constructed.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Token data store – this is a central repository for the token mapping process that holds the original sensitive values and their related token values.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Sensitive data and token values must be securely kept in an encrypted format.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Strong key management procedures are required for sensitive data encryption on token data stores.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization and "classic" encryption effectively protect data if implemented properly, and a computer security system may use both.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] While similar in certain regards, tokenization and classic encryption differ in a few key aspects.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Both are cryptographic data security methods and they essentially have the same function, however they do so with differing processes and have different effects on the data they are protecting.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization is a non-mathematical approach that replaces sensitive data with non-sensitive substitutes without altering the type or length of data.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] This is an important distinction from encryption because changes in data length and type can render information unreadable in intermediate systems such as databases.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Tokenized data can still be processed by legacy systems which makes tokenization more flexible than classic encryption.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] In many situations, the encryption process is a constant consumer of processing power, hence such a system needs significant expenditures in specialized hardware and software.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Another difference is that tokens require significantly less computational resources to process.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] With tokenization, specific data is kept fully or partially visible for processing and analytics while sensitive information is kept hidden.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] This allows tokenized data to be processed more quickly and reduces the strain on system resources.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] This can be a key advantage in systems that rely on high performance.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] In comparison to encryption, tokenization technologies reduce time, expense, and administrative effort while enabling teamwork and communication.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] There are many ways that tokens can be classified.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] However, there is currently no unified classification.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Tokens can be single or multi-use, cryptographic or non-cryptographic, reversible or irreversible, authenticable or non-authenticable, and various combinations thereof.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] In the context of payments, the difference between high and low value tokens plays a significant role.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] High-value tokens (HVT) serve as surrogates for actual PANs in payment transactions and are used as an instrument for completing a payment transaction.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] In order to function, they must look like actual PANs.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Multiple HVT can map back to a single PAN and a single physical credit card without the owner being aware of it.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Additionally, HVT can be limited to certain networks and/or merchants whereas PANs cannot.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] HVT can also be bound to specific devices so that anomalies between token use, physical devices, and geographic locations can be flagged as potentially fraudulent.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] HVT blocking enhances efficiency by reducing computational costs while maintaining accuracy and reducing record linkage as it reduces the number of records that are compared.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Low-value tokens (LVT) also act as surrogates for actual PANs in payment transactions, however they serve a different purpose.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] LVT cannot be used by themselves to complete a payment transaction.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] In order for an LVT to function, it must be possible to match it back to the actual PAN it represents, albeit only in a tightly controlled fashion.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Using tokens to protect PANs becomes ineffectual if a tokenization system is breached, therefore securing the tokenization system itself is extremely important.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] First generation tokenization systems use a database to map from live data to surrogate substitute tokens and back.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] This requires the storage, management, and continuous backup for every new transaction added to the token database to avoid data loss.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Another problem is ensuring consistency across data centers, requiring continuous synchronization of token databases.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Significant consistency, availability and performance trade-offs, per the CAP theorem, are unavoidable with this approach.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] This overhead adds complexity to real-time transaction processing to avoid data loss and to assure data integrity across data centers, and also limits scale.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Storing all sensitive data in one service creates an attractive target for attack and compromise, and introduces privacy and legal risk in the aggregation of data Internet privacy, particularly in the EU.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Another limitation of tokenization technologies is measuring the level of security for a given solution through independent validation.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] With the lack of standards, the latter is critical to establish the strength of tokenization offered when tokens are used for regulatory compliance.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] The method of generating tokens may also have limitations from a security perspective.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] With concerns about security and attacks to random number generators, which are a common choice for the generation of tokens and token mapping tables, scrutiny must be applied to ensure proven and validated methods are used versus arbitrary design.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Random-number generators have limitations in terms of speed, entropy, seeding and bias, and security properties must be carefully analysed and measured to avoid predictability and compromise.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Stateless tokenization allows live data elements to be mapped to surrogate values randomly, without relying on a database, while maintaining the isolation properties of tokenization.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] November 2014, American Express released its token service which meets the EMV tokenization standard.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Other notable examples of tokenization-based payment systems, according to the EMVCo standard, include Google Wallet, Apple Pay, Samsung Pay, Microsoft Wallet, Fitbit Pay and Garmin Pay.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Visa uses tokenization techniques to provide a secure online and mobile shopping.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Using blockchain, as opposed to relying on trusted third parties, it is possible to run highly accessible, tamper-resistant databases for transactions.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] With help of blockchain, tokenization is the process of converting the value of a tangible or intangible asset into a token that can be exchanged on the network.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] This enables the tokenization of conventional financial assets, for instance, by transforming rights into a digital token backed by the asset itself using blockchain technology.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Besides that, tokenization enables the simple and efficient compartmentalization and management of data across multiple users.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Individual tokens created through tokenization can be used to split ownership and partially resell an asset.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Consequently, only entities with the appropriate token can access the data.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Numerous blockchain companies support asset tokenization.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] In 2019, eToro acquired Firmo and renamed as eToroX.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Through its Token Management Suite, which is backed by USD-pegged stablecoins, eToroX enables asset tokenization.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] The tokenization of equity is facilitated by STOKR, a platform that links investors with small and medium-sized businesses.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Tokens issued through the STOKR platform are legally recognized as transferable securities under European Union capital market regulations.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Breakers enable tokenization of intellectual property, allowing content creators to issue their own digital tokens.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Tokens can be distributed to a variety of project participants.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Without intermediaries or governing body, content creators can integrate reward-sharing features into the token.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Building an alternate payments system requires a number of entities working together in order to deliver near field communication (NFC) or other technology based payment services to the end users.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] One of the issues is the interoperability between the players and to resolve this issue the role of trusted service manager (TSM) is proposed to establish a technical link between mobile network operators (MNO) and providers of services, so that these entities can work together.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization can play a role in mediating such services.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization as a security strategy lies in the ability to replace a real card number with a surrogate (target removal) and the subsequent limitations placed on the surrogate card number (risk reduction).
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] If the surrogate value can be used in an unlimited fashion or even in a broadly applicable manner, the token value gains as much value as the real credit card number.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] In these cases, the token may be secured by a second dynamic token that is unique for each transaction and also associated to a specific payment card.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Example of dynamic, transaction-specific tokens include cryptograms used in the EMV (Europay, Mastercard, and Visa) specification.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard, an industry-wide set of guidelines that must be met by any organization that stores, processes, or transmits cardholder data, mandates that credit card data must be protected when stored.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization, as applied to payment card data, is often implemented to meet this mandate, replacing credit card and automated clearing house (ACH) numbers in some systems with a random value or string of characters.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Tokens can be formatted in a variety of ways.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Some token service providers or tokenization products generate the surrogate values in such a way as to match the format of the original sensitive data.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] In the case of payment card data, a token might be the same length as a primary account number (bank card number) and contain elements of the original data such as the last four digits of the card number.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] When a payment card authorization request is made to verify the legitimacy of a transaction, a token might be returned to the merchant instead of the card number, along with the authorization code for the transaction.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] The token is stored in the receiving system while the actual cardholder data is mapped to the token in a secure tokenization system.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Storage of tokens and payment card data must comply with current PCI standards, including the use of strong cryptography.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization is currently in standards definition in ANSI X9 as X9.119 Part 2.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] X9 is responsible for the industry standards for financial cryptography and data protection including payment card PIN management, credit and debit card encryption and related technologies and processes.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] The PCI Council has also stated support for tokenization in reducing risk in data breaches, when combined with other technologies such as Point-to-Point Encryption (P2PE) and assessments of compliance to PCI DSS guidelines.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Visa Inc. released Visa Tokenization Best Practices for tokenization uses in credit and debit card handling applications and services.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] In March 2014, EMVCo LLC released its first payment tokenization specification for EMV.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] PCI DSS is the most frequently utilized standard for Tokenization systems used by payment industry players.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization can render it more difficult for attackers to gain access to sensitive data outside of the tokenization system or service.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Implementation of tokenization may simplify the requirements of the PCI DSS, as systems that no longer store or process sensitive data may have a reduction of applicable controls required by the PCI DSS guidelines.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] This validation is particularly important in tokenization, as the tokens are shared externally in general use and thus exposed in high risk, low trust environments.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] The infeasibility of reversing a token or set of tokens to a live sensitive data must be established using industry accepted measurements and proofs by appropriate experts independent of the service or solution provider.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Not all organizational data can be tokenized, and needs to be examined and filtered.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] When databases are utilized on a large scale, they expand exponentially, causing the search process to take longer, restricting system performance, and increasing backup processes.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] A database that links sensitive information to tokens is called a vault.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] With the addition of new data, the vault's maintenance workload increases significantly.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] For ensuring database consistency, token databases need to be continuously synchronized.
[src:format-preserving-encryption/tokenization-data-security] Apart from that, secure communication channels must be built between sensitive data and the vault so that data is not compromised on the way to or from storage.
